				<h1><a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/post/troubleshooting-configure-make-and-make-install-tutorial">Troubleshooting ./configure, make and make install Tutorial</a></h1>
				<div class="metaRight">
				<img src="../wp-content/themes/colorbold/images/ico_user.png" alt="Author" /> <a href="../post/2007/01" title="Visit rechosen&#8217;s website" rel="external">rechosen</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="../wp-content/themes/colorbold/images/ico_folder.png" alt="Category" /> <a href="tutorials" title="View all posts in Tutorials" rel="category tag">Tutorials</a>	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="../wp-content/themes/colorbold/images/ico_tag.png" alt="Tags" />  <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/tag/configure" rel="nofollow tag">configure</a>, <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/tag/make" rel="nofollow tag">make</a>, <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/tag/make-install" rel="nofollow tag">make install</a>, <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/tag/troubleshooting" rel="nofollow tag">troubleshooting</a></div>
				<p>Sometimes, the typical sequence to compile a program doesn't work. It starts spitting out all kinds of errors and seems to do everything but compiling that annoying program already. What to do then? This tutorial describes how to get rid of many frequently occuring errors during a typical Linux compiling sequence.</p>
<p><em><strong>Note: You should only compile software when you really need to do it. Compiling can be dangerous to your Linux installation. If you want to install some software, please look for a precompiled package (like a .rpm or a .deb) first. If you really need to compile, do it with care.</strong></em> <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/post/troubleshooting-configure-make-and-make-install-tutorial#more-26" class="more-link">read more</a></p>
 
